{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_017TQGYYSA73yJebWdy1HVAg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the spreadsheet formula engine to determine the minimum test level needed and assess what test infrastructure would be required to catch a real failure.\n\nI need to think about:\n- Unit: single function, no I/O\n- Integration: multiple modules, local DB/filesystem\n- System: subprocess, OS, real HTTP, real external API\n- Agentic: real LLM or AI/ML model (non-deterministic)\n- Workflow: multiple agentic steps in sequence\n\nLet me go through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: A cell containing `=SUM(A1:A10)` evaluates to the correct sum**\n- This is purely computational logic\n- Mock-miss: A mock would easily catch range parsing and summation\n- Real-infra: No OS/network/subprocess needed\n- Mock-hide: No, mocking range/cells would still work\n- LLM-dep: No, SUM is deterministic\n- This is straightforward Unit level testing - we can create cell values in memory and verify the formula evaluates correctly\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 2: A cell referencing another cell that contains a formula (cascaded)**\n- Example: B1 = `=A1*2`, C1 = `=B1+1`\n- This requires the formula resolution engine to work correctly\n- Mock-miss: A mock could easily miss if the evaluation order is wrong\n- Real-infra: No OS/network needed\n- LLM-dep: No, this is deterministic\n- This requires testing the cell dependency graph and evaluation order\n- Could be Unit if we properly structure the test, but there's a real risk: if the evaluation engine doesn't properly handle formula-in-formula, a unit test with proper mocking might still pass while the real thing fails\n- Actually, this is Unit-level - we're testing in-process formula resolution with no I/O\n\n\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.9, Integration 0.1, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 3: Detecting circular dependencies (A1→B1→A1)**\n- This is graph cycle detection logic that can be verified with in-memory graph structures\n- No external infrastructure needed\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 4: VLOOKUP exact match and error handling**\n- This is a specific function implementation that performs lookups within cell ranges\n- Mock-miss: Could miss if the lookup logic doesn't properly handle edge cases or error conditions\n- Real-infra: No OS/network needed\n- LLM-dep: No\n- Unit-level testing can verify the lookup algorithm with in-process data structures\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.92, Integration 0.08, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 5: IF with nested conditions**\n- Example: `=IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\")`\n- This is conditional evaluation logic that can be tested with simple input values\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 6: CONCATENATE handling empty cells**\n- This is a string concatenation function that needs to handle null or empty cell values correctly\n- Unit-level testing can verify the function behavior directly\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 7: Formula referencing cell in different sheet**\n- Example: `=Sheet2!A1+1`\n- This requires multi-sheet workbook structure and cross-sheet reference resolution, which is more complex than single-sheet formulas but still testable in-process with a properly constructed workbook object\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.90, Integration 0.10, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 8: When a referenced cell's value changes, all dependent formulas recalculate in topological order**\n- This is the recalculation engine that needs to build a dependency graph, perform topological sorting, and execute recalculations in the correct order\n- The complexity here is that incorrect topological ordering might not be caught by simple tests, so careful test design is needed to verify the ordering explicitly\n- Minimum level: Unit\n- Confidence: Unit 0.85, Integration 0.15, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n**Behavior 9: Undo operation rest ores formula text and computed dependent values**\n- This requires state snapshots, formula text preservation, and dependent value recomputation when undoing\n- The key distinction is whether undo uses an in-memory stack or relies on external persistence like file I/O or databases\n- If implemented as an in-memory stack, it's Unit; if it involves persistence mechanisms, it moves to Integration\n- Minimum level: Unit (for in-memory) or Integration (if persistence is involved)\n- Confidence: Unit 0.7, Integration 0.3\n\n**Behavior 10: Save to disk and load back produces identical values**\n- File I/O and deserialization are non-negotiable here, making this inherently an Integration test\n- Floating-point precision becomes critical—binary format, endianness, and encoding issues can all cause failures that only surface with real disk operations\n- Mocking file I/O would miss real-world scenarios like permission errors or corruption\n- Minimum level: Integration\n- Confidence: Integration 0.95, System 0.05\n\nFor behavior 9 (undo), the question is whether a unit test with mocks can reliably verify that both formula text and dependent values are restored. If state management is straightforward and in-memory, mocking works; but complex caching or lazy evaluation might slip through. I'd lean toward Unit with moderate confidence, supplemented by Integration tests.\n\nBehavior 8 (topological recalculation) hinges on verifying the correct order—if A→B→C and A changes, B then C must recalculate in sequence. A mock-based test risks accidentally passing even if the order is wrong, since mocks don't enforce dependency constraints the way real calculations do.\n\nFor behavior 7 (cross-sheet references), the failure modes—missing sheets, invalid cells, wrong cell resolution, stale references after renaming—are all logic issues that unit tests can catch. These don't require actual file I/O or multi-process coordination, so Unit testing is sufficient with careful assertions on the reference resolution logic.\n\nBehavior 2 involves cascaded formula evaluation where dependent cells must receive computed values rather than formula text, and evaluation order matters. A unit test can verify this by checking that when B1 contains a formula and C1 references B1, C1 gets the evaluated result. For behavior 8, mocking the dependency graph could mask sorting bugs, but designing tests to verify actual traversal of the dependency graph keeps this at the unit level.\n\nFor behavior 9 (undo), the test infrastructure classification depends on how workbook state is managed. If undo relies on an in-memory stack, unit testing suffices by creating a workbook, editing a formula, calling undo, and verifying both the formula text and dependent values are restored. However, if the engine persists workbooks to disk or database to test undo across sessions, integration testing becomes necessary.\n\nI'll assign this as Integration (0.65, 0.35, 0, 0, 0).\n\nMy final classifications are: SUM function Unit (0.95, 0.05, 0, 0, 0), cascaded formula evaluation Unit (0.9, 0.1, 0, 0, 0), circular dependency detection Unit (0.95, 0.05, 0, 0, 0), VLOOKUP Unit (0.95, 0.05, 0, 0, 0), IF nested conditions Unit (0.95, 0.05, 0, 0, 0), CONCATENATE Unit (0.95, 0.05, 0, 0, 0), cross-sheet references Unit (0.9, 0.1, 0, 0, 0), recalculation in topological order Unit (0.85, 0.15, 0, 0, 0), and undo restores formulas and values Integration (0.65, 0.35, 0, 0, 0).\n\nFor save and load producing identical values, that's clearly Integration (0, 0.95, 0.05, 0, 0) since it requires file I/O.\n\nActually, reconsidering the undo test—if it's just an in-memory state stack capturing snapshots before edits, the entire operation stays in-process without file operations, making it Unit. The test would create formulas, modify one, trigger undo, and verify the old formula and computed values return. But there's potential complexity depending on implementation details. So Integration testing is sufficient unless we're testing edge cases like disk full scenarios. I'll stick with Integration 0.95, System 0.05.\n\nFor cascaded evaluation, the core logic runs in-process, so Unit testing should be adequate unless the engine uses lazy evaluation with disk-based caching. For the basic requirement, Unit 0.9, Integration 0.1 seems right.\n\nOn topological ordering, a well-constructed unit test with proper mocking should catch ordering failures if the dependency graph is set up correctly and recalculation sequences are verified. The real question is whether there's an in-process failure mode that only manifests during integration testing.\n\nConcurrency issues would require System-level testing, but since the behavior doesn't mention concurrent modifications, Unit testing is appropriate here. Unit 0.85, Integration 0.15 reflects this.\n\nNow I need to ensure my test descriptions actually match the minimum levels I've chosen, and that plan_consistent is true for each behavior. For the SUM function specifically, I can create cells with known values and verify the sum calculation works correctly—a straightforward unit test.\n\nFor cascaded formulas, I'd set up A1=5, B1=A1*2, C1=B1+1 and confirm C1 evaluates to 11, testing dependency resolution without external systems. Circular dependencies can be caught by creating A1=B1+1 and B1=A1+1, then verifying the circular reference error is raised. VLOOKUP behavior is testable by creating a lookup table and confirming it returns the correct value or an appropriate error for missing keys. Nested IF statements can be tested by providing various inputs and checking the outputs match expected results. Each of these is purely in-process logic that doesn't require integration with other systems.\n\nString concatenation with CONCATENATE can be verified by combining text cells and empty cells, ensuring the function handles them correctly. Cross-sheet references require multiple sheets where I reference data across them and confirm the resolution works as expected. For topological recalculation, I'd create a dependency chain, modify the base cell, and verify all dependents update in the correct order—though I need to ensure the test actually validates that ordering. Undo behavior is trickier: if it's purely in-memory, it's a unit test, but if it needs to verify restoration across save/load cycles, it becomes integration-level. The core behavior involves restoring both the formula text and all previously computed dependent values after editing. For behavior 9, the undo mechanism needs to restore both the formula text and computed values of dependent cells. Since this can be handled entirely through in-process state snapshots without requiring persistence, it fits at the Unit level. The key distinction is that when a formula changes (like from =A1+1 to =A1*2), undo must capture and restore the previous formula along with its calculated results—this is internal state management rather than external I/O. I'm confident this is Unit-level with high probability, leaving minimal chance for Integration or higher classifications. sheet references are resolved within the process. Topological ordering of dependencies and graph traversal for cycle detection are both algorithmic operations on in-memory structures. State snapshots for undo capture and restore in-process data without touching external systems.\n\nFor the save/load behavior, file I/O and serialization cross the boundary into Integration testing since they involve actual disk operations.\n\nNow for the test specifics: SUM needs to verify the formula correctly aggregates a range of values—I'd set up cells A1 through A10 with known numbers, write a formula that sums them, and confirm the result matches manual calculation. I should test edge cases like the first and last cells in the range, and ensure it handles both integers and decimals accurately. The other behaviors follow similar patterns—each tests the core algorithmic or computational logic without external dependencies, except for save/load which requires actual file operations.\n\nCascaded formulas require verifying that when one cell references another's computed value, the chain resolves correctly. If A1 holds 5, B1 contains =A1*2, and C1 contains =B1+1, then C1 should evaluate to 11. When A1 changes to 10, both B1 and C1 should automatically recalculate to 20 and 21. This is purely in-process evaluation logic—the engine must track which cells depend on which, compute them in the right order, and use the computed values rather than formula text.\n\nCircular dependencies need detection logic that identifies when cells reference each other in a loop. If A1 references B1 and B1 references A1, the engine should catch this and return an error like #CIRC or #REF. Direct cycles are the obvious case, but indirect chains matter too.\n\nFor VLOOKUP, I need to test exact matches returning the correct value, missing keys returning #N/A, and edge cases like empty tables or NULL keys. The function should locate the right column value from the lookup table.\n\nFor nested IF conditions, I'm testing formulas like =IF(A1>10, IF(A1>20, \"high\", \"medium\"), \"low\") with boundary values (5, 15, 25) and NULL inputs to ensure each branch evaluates correctly.\n\nCONCATENATE is a pure string operation on in-process values, so unit tests can verify text joining, empty cell handling, and separator logic across different input combinations without external dependencies.\n\n7. **Cross-sheet references**\n   - Minimum level: Unit\n   - Test description: Create a workbook with multiple sheets, place a value in Sheet2!A1, then in Sheet1 create a formula =Sheet2!A1+1 and verify it resolves correctly. Test error cases like referencing non-existent sheets and missing cells, ensuring proper parsing and resolution in both directions.\n   - Justification: Cross-sheet reference resolution is deterministic in-process logic that can be fully tested with multiple sheets in memory. No external dependencies or I/O required.\n   - Probabilities: Unit 0.95, Integration 0.05, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n8. **Recalculation in topological order**\n   - Minimum level: Unit\n   - Test description: Build a dependency chain where A1=5, B1=A1*2, C1=B1+1, D1=A1+C1. Change A1 to 10 and confirm all dependents recalculate in the correct order (B1 before C1 before D1), with each cell using the updated values from its dependencies.\n   - Justification: Topological recalculation is a deterministic ordering problem within the evaluation engine that can be tested entirely in-memory with a controlled dependency graph.\n   - Probabilities: Unit 0.9, Integration 0.1, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n9. **Undo restores formulas and values**\n   - Minimum level: Unit\n   - Test description: Set up a workbook containing formulas (A1=5, B1=A1*2 = 10). Modify B\n\n1's formula to =A1*3, confirming it evaluates to 15. Then undo and check that B1's formula reverts to =A1*2, its value returns to 10, and other cells remain unchanged. Include tests for multiple undo/redo cycles.\n   - Justification: Undo is a state management system that preserves snapshots of both formula text and computed values in memory. The test validates that the undo stack correctly captures and restores state without requiring I/O. Failures in capturing formula text or dependent values will surface immediately.\n   - Probabilities: Unit 0.8, Integration 0.2, System 0, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\n10. **Save to disk and load back produces**\n   - Minimum level: Integration\n   - Test description: Build a workbook containing diverse formulas (SUM, VLOOKUP, IF, nested expressions, cross-sheet references, floating-point math) with their computed results. Write it to disk using the engine's serialization format, then load it into a fresh engine instance. Confirm that formula text survives intact, cell values match exactly (including floating-point precision), formulas still point to the right cells, and the workbook can be edited and saved again without corruption.\n   - Justification: Save/load requires actual file I/O and serialization logic that mocks cannot fully exercise. The engine must encode and decode cell data, formulas, and metadata correctly in its binary format. Real file operations expose encoding bugs that unit tests would miss.\n    - Probabilities: Unit 0, Integration 0.95, System 0.05, Agentic 0, Workflow 0\n\nNow checking whether each test matches its assigned level:\n- SUM: Unit fits—formula evaluation happens in-process.\n- Cascaded: Unit fits—dependency resolution is in-process.\n- Circular: Unit fits—cycle detection is in-process.\n- VLOOKUP: Unit fits—function evaluation is in-process.\n- Nested IF: Unit fits—condition evaluation is in-process.\n- CONCATENATE: Unit fits—string handling is in-process.\n- Cross-sheet: Unit fits—reference resolution is in-process.\n- Topological order: Unit fits—graph ordering is in-process, despite higher complexity.\n- Undo: Unit fits—state snapshots are in-process.\n- Save/load: Integration is required—real file I/O is essential.\n\nAll tests align with their levels. Now I'll construct the StructuredOutput.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13918,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13918},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe507edc-fb39-451a-935c-13d4e3fbc945","uuid":"8b88d61d-d717-44